# PR and Git Workflow Standards

## Branch naming

```text
feature/m{N}-{N}-{N}-{short-description}    # milestone work
fix/m{N}-{N}-{N}-{short-description}        # bug fix in milestone
chore/m{N}-{N}-{N}-{short-description}      # infra, deps, docs
hotfix/{short-description}                   # production emergency
```

Examples:
- `feature/m1-1-7-users-agents-schema`
- `chore/m1-3-3-shared-logger-package`
- `fix/m1-2-4-rate-limit-key-format`

## Commit messages — Conventional Commits

```text
{type}({scope}): {imperative description}

[body: WHY this change, not WHAT]

[footer: closes #issue, breaking changes]
```

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `chore`, `docs`, `test`, `perf`, `refactor`, `ci`

```text
# WRONG — no type, no scope, past tense, vague
fixed the rate limiter
updated code
made changes

# RIGHT
feat(proxy): add org-level rate limit skeleton with Redis sliding window

Implements the soft rate limiter described in ADR-0015.
Uses INCR+EXPIRE rather than Lua scripts; the race window is
documented and tested with TestRedisSlider_ConcurrentBurst.
Phase 4 will replace RedisSlider with a Lua atomic implementation.

Closes #42
```

## PR description — fill every section of the template

Required sections:
- **What and Why**: What changed and why this PR exists
- **How**: Key design decisions; link to ADR if one was written
- **Testing**: What tests were added; how to run them locally
- **Performance**: Latency/throughput impact if measurable
- **Security**: Any security implications; auth/permission changes
- **Migrations / Ops**: DB migrations, env var changes, deploy order
- **Docs**: What documentation was updated
- **Definition of Done**: Checklist against milestone acceptance criteria

## PR size — small, reviewable, single concern

- Target: ≤400 lines changed (excluding generated files and migrations)
- Maximum: 800 lines (requires justification in PR description)
- Never mix refactoring and features in one PR
- Migrations always in their own PR from the feature that uses them

## Code review standards

Every PR requires review from at least one other contributor. Reviewers check:

1. Does the code match the milestone acceptance criteria?
2. Are the complexity limits respected (no function >40 lines, no nesting >3)?
3. Are all error returns handled?
4. Does every new function have a doc comment?
5. Are new env vars documented in `.env.example` and `ENVIRONMENT_VARIABLES.md`?
6. Is there a test for every new behaviour, including failure modes?
7. Is there a test for every security boundary?
